# migrated from tests/cases/algebra.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test algebra]
# gen107 (L17): one-step algebra. gen35 could COMPUTE a op b; L17 INVERTS it —
# given an equation with one unknown and one operation, solve for the unknown by
# applying the inverse operation. The unknown is never on the answer side to
# begin with, so this is a genuine reasoning step, not a lookup. Held-out
# numbers and phrasings; the same number parsing/formatting as mod_arith.

# Addition: unknown on the left -> subtract.
> x + 3 = 7
< x = 4.
# The proof shows the inversion it performed, derived from the equation itself.
> how do you know?
< Because x + 3 = 7, so x = 7 - 3 = 4.

# Subtraction inverts to addition.
> x - 4 = 1
< x = 5.

# Multiplication inverts to division.
> 2 * x = 10
< x = 5.

# Division inverts to multiplication; unknown in the denominator works too.
> x / 3 = 6
< x = 18.
> 20 / x = 4
< x = 5.

# The unknown can be any identifier and sit in any operand slot.
> 12 + n = 30
< n = 18.

# The equation may be written with the operation on the RIGHT of the '=' too.
> 5 = x - 2
< x = 7.

# Plain arithmetic (no '=') is untouched: it still falls through to mod_arith.
> what is 2 + 2
< 4.

# No finite solution (would divide by zero) -> decline honestly, never invent.
> 10 / x = 0
< I don't understand that yet.
